=========================================
DEQUE (DOUBLE ENDED QUEUE) – INTERVIEW NOTES
=========================================

1. What is deque?
-----------------
- deque = Double Ended Queue (STL container)
- Supports insertion/deletion at BOTH ends
- Provides O(1) random access
- More flexible than vector for front operations

-----------------------------------------

2. Internal Working (VERY IMPORTANT)

=========================================================
Interview One-Liner
=========================================================

std::deque is implemented as a map (array of pointers)
pointing to multiple fixed-size memory blocks. Because
elements are stored in blocks instead of one contiguous
array, deque can efficiently insert/delete at both front
and back while still providing O(1) random access.

Deque is NOT contiguous memory.

It uses:
- A MAP (array of pointers)
- Multiple FIXED-SIZE MEMORY BLOCKS

Structure:

Map (Array of pointers)

        +-----+-----+-----+
        |  *  |  *  |  *  |
        +-----+-----+-----+
           |      |      |
           v      v      v

      +----+----+    +----+----+    +----+----+
      |10  |20  |    |30  |40  |    |50  |60  |
      +----+----+    +----+----+    +----+----+

deque stores data in MULTIPLE FIXED-SIZE BLOCKS.

A small array called MAP stores pointers to these blocks.
=========================================================
Why not use contiguous memory?
=========================================================

Suppose we have:

[10][20][30][40]

push_front(5)

In vector:
Need to shift all elements.

[5][10][20][30][40]

Cost = O(n)

In deque:

Allocate another block at front and place 5.

      +----+
      | 5  |
      +----+
          |
Map ---> [Block1][Block2][Block3]

No shifting required.

Cost ≈ O(1)

-----------------------------------------

3. How element access works

For index i:

block_index  = i / block_size
offset       = i % block_size

Access:
map[block_index][offset]

👉 Gives O(1) random access

-----------------------------------------

4. Vector vs Deque (VERY IMPORTANT)*************IIIMP

VECTOR:
- Single contiguous memory
- Fast cache performance*****
- O(n) push_front (shifting required)

DEQUE:
- Multiple memory blocks
- Slightly slower cache performance  ******
- O(1) push_front and push_back

Visual Interview Explanation
Vector
RAM:

[10][20][30][40][50][60][70][80]
^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
One cache line may contain many elements.

Sequential access is very fast.

Deque
RAM:

Block1: [10][20]
                (far away)
Block2: [30][40]
                (far away)
Block3: [50][60]

CPU cache cannot efficiently prefetch all elements.***********
Vector is cache-friendly because its elements are stored contiguously, so loading one element often loads nearby elements into the CPU cache as well. 
Deque stores elements in multiple blocks scattered in memory, causing more cache misses and slightly slower iteration.

-----------------------------------------

5. Time Complexity

Access [] / at()     : O(1)
push_back()          : O(1)
push_front()         : O(1)
pop_back()           : O(1)
pop_front()          : O(1)
insert/erase middle  : O(n)
size()               : O(1)

-----------------------------------------

6. Why deque is faster at front?

Vector:
[10][20][30]
Insert front → shift all → O(n)

Deque:
Adds new block or uses front space
No shifting → O(1)

-----------------------------------------

7. Why deque is NOT contiguous?

Because:
- elements are stored in multiple blocks
- blocks can be anywhere in memory

So:
vector → contiguous
deque  → non-contiguous

-----------------------------------------

8. Iterator Invalidation

Invalidation may happen on:
- insert / erase
- reallocation of map
- structural changes

👉 Iterators are NOT fully stable like list

-----------------------------------------

9. Key Features

✔ O(1) push_front
✔ O(1) push_back
✔ O(1) random access
✔ flexible memory allocation
❌ not contiguous memory
❌ slightly worse cache locality

-----------------------------------------

10. When to use deque?

Use deque when:
- frequent push_front()
- frequent pop_front()
- need both-end operations

Example:
- sliding window
- BFS queues
- task scheduling

Use vector when:
- mostly push_back()
- cache performance important
- need contiguous memory

